**CORS = browser blocking cross-origin requests.** Happens when JS on `domain-a.com` fetches from `domain-b.com` without permission.

**Common causes:**

| Cause | Fix |
|-------|-----|
| Server missing `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header | Add it server-side |
| Preflight (`OPTIONS`) request not handled | Server must respond to `OPTIONS` with CORS headers |
| Credentials + wildcard origin | Can't use `*` with `credentials: 'include'` — set explicit origin |
| HTTP → HTTPS mismatch | Treat as different origin; use same protocol |
| Dev hitting prod API | Add `localhost` to server's allowed origins |

**Quick server fixes:**

```js
// Express
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', 'https://your-frontend.com');
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Methods', 'GET,POST,PUT,DELETE,OPTIONS');
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type, Authorization');
  if (req.method === 'OPTIONS') return res.sendStatus(204);
  next();
});
```

```python
# FastAPI
from fastapi.middleware.cors import CORSMiddleware
app.add_middleware(CORSMiddleware, allow_origins=["https://your-frontend.com"], ...)
```

**Key rule:** CORS is always fixed **server-side**. Browser enforces it — you can't bypass from the client (and shouldn't try).

